		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />Here is the $2004 read according to Nintendulator:<br /><br /><div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">int&nbsp; &nbsp;__fastcall&nbsp; &nbsp;Read4 (void)<br />{<br />&nbsp; &nbsp;if (IsRendering)<br />&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;readLatch = Sprite&#91;SpritePtr&#93;;<br />&nbsp; &nbsp;else&nbsp; &nbsp;readLatch = Sprite&#91;SprAddr&#93;;<br />&nbsp; &nbsp;return readLatch;<br />}</div><br /><br />The Sprite array appears to represent both primary and secondary OAM.<br /><br />According to the wiki:<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">Reading OAMDATA while the PPU is rendering will expose internal OAM accesses during sprite evaluation and loading; Micro Machines does this. It used to be thought that reading from this register wasn't reliable, however more recent evidence seems to suggest that this is solely due to corruption by OAMADDR writes.  In the oldest instantiations of the PPU, as found on earlier Famicoms, this register is not readable. It's not known exactly which revision of the 2C02 added the readabilityâ€”it is certainly absent in the RP2C02C, and present by the RP2C02G.</div><br /><br />Can someone please provide more information?  The wiki seems incomplete.<br /><br />Edit: On a side note, FCEUX 2.2.1 looks more screwed up than my emulator:<br /><br /><img src="http://i.imgur.com/O4NoO1k.png" alt="Image" /><br /><br /><img src="http://i.imgur.com/d1mpB0r.png" alt="Image" />

		

